European inflation declined in food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the dizzying growth in food prices.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, registering - after 2.6 percent of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the EU Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts only gave as likely a 3 percent - announced Bloomberg.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decrease, along with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "there is a need to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene later on.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, beat the record for twelve years; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation occurred in the euro area as a result of galloping food and energy prices.
Wheat-term contributions increased by 88 percent and soy-quotation has reached its maximum level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching as early as last month the black gold almost 100 dollars the barrel.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will fall from 2.1 percent current to 2.5 percent, but by 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will be maintained in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, it is expected that during 2008 the ECB will double the interest rates.
