In many hospitals you save with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been reported in hospitals, primarily due to the improper application of antibiotics.
The conditions of hygiene prevailing in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and overload of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the department-medical chief of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many hospitals it saves even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, an MRIS contagion has been diagnosed in the trauma department of the Hospital János.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital early in the year.
A serious car accident wound was discharged from the hospital and the same patient had to return to the hospital shortly after the infection with MRSA and since then there has been no significant surgical intervention by the presence of the bacteria in her body.
Up to 10 December this year, they have been registered in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multi-resistant agents - said Karolina Böröcz, department doctor-head of the National Center of Epidemiology.
This means that this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has certainly been recorded in hospitals, but no information is available.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, methicillin-oxacylin-resistant.
One third of humans carry in their nose the bacteria of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. inflammation of the throat, amygdalitis, skin infections, wounds) respond well to antibiotics and are easily treated.
However, once it is applied excessively or improperly to antibiotics, bacteria that usually react well to antibiotics become bacteria that are very resistant to antibiotics and quickly become contaminated in inadequate hospital conditions.
They may cause serious hospital infections, such as injuries or septicemia first to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened body, to elderly or to persons with low weight.
In the opinion of the hospital doctor-director János, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where his presence is not examined.
Antibiotics resistant
"These patients are isolated, nursing staff care for them in rubber gloves and masks and there are the appropriate antibiotics for their treatment," Tibor Nyulasi said.
Patients hospitalized are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but it cannot even prevent infection in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA's hospital infections in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of training and infection with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the patients that carry MRSA in their body.
However, in Hungarian hospitals it is not fashionable to take microbiological samples.
This is also because the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most of the cases go out to the public when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient - said the department chief-doctor of the epidemiological center.
The European Union strongly commends the application of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological tables.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is directed, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Taking microbiological samples is even less common in the case of travelling patients or in the primary care - Karolina Böröcz said.
Saving with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through health personnel.
Therefore, they play a very important role in hand-washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks, but also in this sense there are considerable deficiencies in hospitals.
MRSA was infected by drop-on transmission and direct contact between individuals, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately you can also experience – added Karolina Böröcz – that in hospitals with less favourable economic situation saves with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for infection.
In Karolina Böröcz's view, where appropriate prevention measures are carried out, fewer infections of this type are observed or the pathogen's infection may be stopped.
Government Programme against MRSA
Treatment of contact with MRSA is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is being fought against.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The program appears to be successful, according to the data provided, infections with MRSA show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and that of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
